entry.title: Improve column balancing for IFC-floats.
entry.content:
Space shortage caused by float breaks wasn't propagated correctly for

floats inside an inline formatting context, resulting in column

balancing problems, typically over-stretching.



Let PositionFloat() create a break-before break token, instead of

requiring every call site to do it. Also propagate space shortage here.



This required that space shortage propagation code were moved up from

NGBoxFragmentBuilder to NGFragmentBuilder, so that it can be used with

NGLineBoxFragmentBuilder can use it as well. Since this is closely tied

with another column balancing concept - tallest unbreakable block-size -

also move that one.



Add two tests: One for floats as block children. This was already

working, but there was no test coverage. The other test is for floats as

inline children, and this wasn't working without this CL.

> PDF a11y: Create the status node to notify users of PDF content loading

>

> Make the status node available regardless of the PDF OCR feature to

> notify users of PDF content loading. This status node will be added and

> become available when it starts to load PDF content into an a11y tree.

> Then, the status node will be deleted once it finishes loading the

> PDF content into the tree.

>

> Note that this status node will be kept when PDF OCR is on and PDF

entry.title: PDF a11y: Create the status node to notify users of PDF content loading
entry.content:
Make the status node available regardless of the PDF OCR feature to

notify users of PDF content loading. This status node will be added and

become available when it starts to load PDF content into an a11y tree.

Then, the status node will be deleted once it finishes loading the

PDF content into the tree.



Note that this status node will be kept when PDF OCR is on and PDF

doesn't have accessible text but images without alternative text.



This notification is necessary especially when users open a large PDF

(e.g. 200 or more pages) as it takes one or more minutes to load such

a large PDF. Without notification, users won't have any accessible

information that helps them know what's going on after opening a PDF

until it finishes loading the PDF content into an a11y tree.

entry.title: [TSF] Deny lock to TEXT_INPUT_TYPE_NONE in RequestLock.
entry.content:
There are scenarios where the text input type can switch to NONE before the composition can be cancelled by TSF. In these cases we deny the document lock in RequestLock API by returning E_FAIL. This is similar to what we do for dummy TSF text stores.

e.g.

- UpdateTextInputState is called that switches the text input to NONE.

- Calls InputMethodWinTSF::OnTextInputTypeChanged that first tries to cancel the composition if there is any.

- This reentrantly calls into TSF's RequestLock API where it tries to commit previously composed text, but the text input type has already switched to NONE, so it fails in the text input client.

entry.title: Fix race condition in HlsManifestDemuxerEngine teardown
entry.content:
Sequence diagram for issue (double lines are posted tasks)

Media Thread Main Thread



** HMDE::ReadStream

│

v

HMDE::ReadChunk ═══════════════════════════> MBDS::ReadTask

│

v

HMDE::ExchangeStreamID <════════════════════ MBDS::ReadOp::Run

║

** HMDE::Stop ═════════════════════════════> DSP::Reset

║ │

v v

Rendition::OnSegmentData ~BufferedDataSourceHost

│

v

Rendition::FetchNext

|

v

HMDE::ReadChunk ═══════════════════════════> MBDS::ReadTask

│

v

UAF on `host_`



There are two issues at play here - one is that HlsManifestDemuxerEngine

was allowing calls to ::ReadChunk after ::Stop, and the other was that

almost all calls to ::ReadChunk were binding with a task post. This task

post was necessary before ::ExchangeStreamId was introduced, but is now

causing an issue where a ::Stop call can happen between the two.

entry.title: [Discounts] Rate control for showing the OfferNotificationBubbleView
entry.content:
automatically



Before this change, the OfferNotificationBubbleView shows automatically

for those new offers that are not shown before.



With this change, the new triggering logic is:

* If the committed url contains the correct UTM tag info, the bubble

will always show automatically. Otherwise,

* If the committed url has merchant-wide-offer available, the bubble

will always be hidden until user explicitly clicks on the icon.

* None of the above, falls back to whether the offer has shown before.

If the offer has shown before, bubble will not show automatically.



Note: We will implement the additional rate control logic for urls with

correct UTM tag info in another CL.

entry.title: Set ssp-buffer-size to the default of 8.
entry.content:
The ssp-buffer-size limit is used to decide if stack protector

checking will be added to a function, if a local variable array

of size 8 or greater is present, the function gets the stack

protector prologue and epilogue added.



For reasons old as time, we set it to 4, which triggers

an interesting LLVM bug: https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/66709



The result of this bug was increased binary size with stack

protector added on functions that do not need it. The compiler

mistakenly counts structure padding as a local array, and adds

the stack protector. With the default of 8 set by this CL,

the unnecessary addition will not normally happen, since the

padding size added to structures will be smaller than 8.



The result will be a decreased binary size (-272K on

android-binary-size).

entry.title: infra: Support links to mirrored/mirroring builders in descriptions
entry.content:
This should allow a viewer to easily map between a CI bot and any try

bot that mirrors it (or vice versa), so long as the builders

involved have migrated their recipe configs to starlark. (We assume

most every chromium bot has.)



And this enables the new descriptions for only builders mirroring

or being mirrored by "GPU FYI Mac Builder". This builder has a lot of

mirrors (see the cr-buildbucket.cfg diff). So we assume it's a good

check of how the descriptions will look. Will expand to all builders

if it looks good.



Note that with the completion of crbug.com/1344925, the description

should be stored on a per-build basis. Meaning: if the description

changes, the description displayed on older builds will still show the

description that was live when the build ran. This is preferred since

it enables us to store somewhat volatile information in the

description. But that may confuse folks if they read the description

from old builds and assume it applies to the builder now. Not sure

how to resolve that. (Maybe show a warning in milo if the old

description != current description?)



Without this change, main.star takes about 3.23s locally. With it, it

takes about 3.28s. (That's the average across 10 runs.)
